1 (A) The radiation power emitted between 250 and 315 nanometers represents at least five per-
2 cent of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers; or
3 (B) The radiation power emitted between 315 and 400 nanometers represents at least 20 percent
4 of the total radiation power emitted between 250 and 800 nanometers.
5 (d) A lamp used for the generation of ozone where the primary purpose is to emit radiation at
6 approximately 185.1 nanometers.
7 (e) A lamp used for coral zooxanthellae symbiosis from which the radiation power emitted be-
8 tween 400 and 480 nanometers represents at least 40 percent of the total radiation power emitted
9 between 250 and 800 nanometers.
10 (f) Any lamp used in an electronic product designed to incorporate one or more ultraviolet lamps
11 and intended for irradiation of any part of the living human body by ultraviolet radiation, with
12 wavelengths in air between 200 and 400 nanometers, to induce skin tanning.
13 (3) A lamp used in a medical device or otherwise used for medical or veterinary diagnosis or
14 treatment.
15 (4) A lamp used in pharmaceutical product manufacturing or quality control.
16 (5) A lamp used for spectroscopy and photometric applications, including ultraviolet-visible
17 spectroscopy, molecular spectroscopy, atomic absorption spectroscopy, nondispersive infrared
18 (NDIR), Fourier transform infrared (FTIR), medical analysis, ellipsometry, layer thickness measure-
19 ment, process monitoring or environmental monitoring.
20 (6) A lamp used by academic or research institutions exclusively for conducting research
21 projects or experiments.
22 (7) A compact fluorescent lamp used to replace a lamp in a motor vehicle manufactured on or
23 before January 1, 2020.
24 (8) A lamp purchased by a school district, as defined in ORS 332.002, for use in school
25 buildings.
26 (9) A lamp purchased by the owner or operator of one or more facilities located in this
27 state that together comprise more than one million square feet for use in the purchaser’s
28 facility. For purposes of this subsection, the square footage of buildings owned or operated
29 by the purchaser’s parent company or subsidiary, or by an entity that is similarly related to
30 the purchaser, may be used to determine the total square footage of buildings owned or op-
31 erated by the purchaser.
